WEBVTT

00:00:00.151 --> 00:00:02.852
Leading congruently requires building trust.

00:00:03.453 --> 00:00:11.277
Interpersonal trust is the willingness to accept vulnerability based on the expectation that another party's behavior will produce a positive outcome.

00:00:12.357 --> 00:00:16.940
Trust is built in small, consistent moments based on four distinct pillars.

00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:22.283
Sincerity means being true to your word, with opinions supported by evidence.

00:00:23.043 --> 00:00:25.484
Reliability means keeping commitments.

00:00:26.205 --> 00:00:31.087
Competence means possessing the required skills and resources to execute duties.

00:00:31.988 --> 00:00:35.690
Care means being genuinely concerned with the interests of others.

00:00:36.690 --> 00:00:38.191
Consider a worked example.

00:00:38.951 --> 00:00:43.314
A leader promises to review a project by Friday, which is sincerity.

00:00:44.314 --> 00:00:49.058
The leader actually completes the review on time, demonstrating reliability.

00:00:49.639 --> 00:00:56.525
The leader provides expert feedback, showing competence, and ensures the team member is not overworked,

00:00:56.885 --> 00:00:57.766
proving care.

00:00:58.707 --> 00:01:00.729
Let us do a tiny check for understanding.

00:01:01.430 --> 00:01:06.314
If a leader consistently shows up to meetings on time, which pillar does this represent?

00:01:07.015 --> 00:01:09.197
Sincerity or reliability?

00:01:10.153 --> 00:01:14.759
The correct answer is reliability because it involves keeping a commitment.

00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:19.765
Noticing the right cue here is an excellent strategy for building trust.
